  "final_answer": "Yes — there are multiple cases where students spend about the same amount of time using AI tools but report very different grade outcomes.\n\nExamples:\n- Around 0.7 hours/day:\n  - Student 30: slight decline\n  - Student 13: improved\n  - Possible differences: purpose (Writing vs Coding), tool used (Grammarly vs Gemini), satisfaction (Medium vs High)\n\n- Around 3.2 hours/day:\n  - Student 9: slight decline\n  - Student 31: improved\n  - Possible differences: purpose (Homework vs Research), satisfaction (Medium vs High)\n\n- Around 4.2 hours/day:\n  - Student 8: slight decline\n  - Student 4: improved\n  - Possible differences: purpose (Coding vs Learning), tool used (Grammarly vs ChatGPT)\n\n- Around 5.0 to 5.2 hours/day:\n  - Student 21: slight decline\n  - Student 18: improved\n  - Possible differences: purpose (Homework vs Coding), tool used (Grammarly vs ChatGPT), education level (School vs University)\n\nMost likely factors explaining the differences:\n- Purpose of AI use\n  - Higher-performing students often used AI for Coding, Research, Learning, or Homework in ways that may support deeper academic work.\n  - Lower-performing students were more often using it for Writing or in less effective task contexts.\n\n- AI tool used\n  - Students with improved grades were often using ChatGPT, Gemini, Copilot, or Notion AI.\n  - Lower-performing students were frequently using Grammarly in these matched comparisons.\n\n- Satisfaction level\n  - Improved students often reported higher satisfaction, which may reflect better fit between the tool and their study needs.\n\n- Education level and academic context\n  - In some pairs, the higher-performing student was at a different education level, which may affect how effectively AI is used.\n\n- Demographics and context\n  - Age, gender, and city also differ across some matched students, but these look more like background factors than the main drivers.\n\nBottom line:\nStudy time alone does not explain academic outcomes. In this dataset, how students use AI, which tool they use, and how satisfied they are with it seem more important than just the number of hours spent.",
